As part of my process of improvement and responsibility to make these sessions accurate and valuable, I listen to them all and will always correct errors made if any

I want to start by clarifying a mistake I made last session

I said that Jesus was a common name, coming from the hebrew name Joseph but Jesus is actually Hebrew for Joshua which means "Yahweh saves"

Yahweh is the Hebrew name for God revealed to Moses at the burning bush in the book of Exodus in the old testament

Something I didn't mention last session but seems important is the meaning of Christ. It's not Jesus' last name

Christ derives from the Greek word Christos meaning anointed one. Translates to messiah in Hebrew meaning "the one who is anointed"

Christ points back to David as the anointed king of Israel and to the promise of an "anointed one", the messiah who would rule God's people


Last week we started the Gospel of Matthew with chapter 1

Quick summary:

Levi was a Jewish tax collector. One day Jesus rocks up and calls Levi to follow him. Levi left his position as a tax collector and became Matthew

Matthew begins with the geneaology of Jesus Christ to demonstrate his legitimacy as the son of David and the son of Abraham

Matthew wrote this gospel for Jews so beginning with legitimizing Jesus by explicitly stating his lineage is important for credibility

Matthew explains the birth of Jesus from his parents Joseph and Mary. Jesus was conceived within Mary by the Holy Spirit

Conception by the Holy Spirit instead of his human father (Joseph), allowed Jesus to be born without the inherent sinful nature inherited from Adam

This is an important point so i'll repeat it

The virgin birth of Jesus by Mary bypassed the inheritance of mans sinful nature inherited from Adam

The miraculour conception allowed Jesus to be fully human (through Mary) while remaining fully divine

Though this, Jesus effectively became a new covenant head to replace Adam

This now brings us to chapter 2

--> verse 1 READ

A few things about Bethlehem

The name means "house of bread" which symbolizes Jesus as the bread of life

Bethlehem is Biblically recognized as the home city and birthplace of King David

First Samuel 17:12 "Now David was the son of an Ephrathite of Bethlehem in Judah named Jesse"

While Jerusalem is also called the city of David because he conquered it, David was born in Bethlehem and lived there as a young shepherd before becoming king 

The prohet Samuel also anointed David as king over Israel in Bethlehem

The connection of Bethlehem with David, who was the greatest king in the history of Israel, reinforces Jesus' messianic lineage

--> verse 1-6 READ

Wise men came. These men were probably astronomers who studied the stars to interpret omens. It doesnt say there was 3 of them 

They came a long distance to honour an infant king

"for we saw his star when it rose" means they saw something unique and extraordinary. God guided these astronomers by a star

Herod was troubled. He was threatened by anything that could disrupt his ruling power

--> verse 7-8 READ

Herod attempts to use the wise men to find the child so he can kill him. Claims he wants to find Jesus to worship him but really wants to kill him

--> verse 9-12

The wise men present gifts to Jesus and leave without telling Herod

Common practice back then was that you wouldnt ever appear before royalty or a person of importance without bringing gifts

More imporant than the gifts is that they worshipped Jesus










-------> BEHAVIOUR (10min)

One of the core elements of our weekly fellowship service is a 10 minute discussion about bevaviours

What behaviours are expected of true Christians? What behaviours should be deleted if we aspire to live righteously

The bible offers us instruction for ther purpose of informing and shaping our actions

The goal isn't just to know Gods word, it's to apply the word in everyday life.

This weeks behaviour is prayer

Why should we pray?
What is prayer?
How should we pray?


--> WHY should we pray? 

What did Jesus say about prayer?

In the Bible, Jesus says to pray in private

Jesus says to avoid empty phrases. No mindless repetition Keep it simple and to the point. God knows what you need. Dont waste his time with fancy words. Make it simple and sincere

He offers us a template of how to pray

Forgiveness is a big part of prayer. Asking God to forgive our sins and forgiving others for their sins against us




-->WHAT is prayer?

A petition to God

A request to the trinity that is God the heavenly father, Jesus Christ Lord of Lords, and the Holy Spirit




--> HOW should we pray?



In Matthew chapter 6, Jesus gives very clear and explicit instruction about prayer

Chapter 6 verse 6: "but when you pray, go into your room and shut the door and pray to your Father who is in secret. Anyour Father who sees in secret will reward you"

Jesus continues in verse 7 saying: "and when you pray, do not heap up empty phrases as the gentiles do, for they think that they will be heard for their many words.

The he says, very clearly in verse 9, "pray like this"

He writes the Lord's prayer which many recite word for word but notice Jesus didn't say "Say this prayer", he said "pray like this"

So he's giving us a template for prayer which consists of an invocation and 6 petitions

--> Invocation: "Our Father in heaven" An invocation is the act of calling upon God. An opening sentence that serves as a request for God's attention 

--> Petition 1: "Hallowed be your name" Petition just means an earnest request made to a higher authority. This first petition is that God's name would be hallowed

Hallowed meaning treated with the highest honour and set apart as holy

--> Petition 2: "Your Kingdom come" The second petition is for the continual advancement of God's kingdom on earth

The presence of God's kingdom in the time after Jesus refers to the reign of Christ in the hearts and lives of believers and to the presence of Christ in his body, the church

True Christians. Genuine believers are called to constantly and increasingly reflect Christ's love, obey his laws, honour him, and proclaim the good news of the kingdom

--> Petitian 3: "your will be done" speaks of God's will

This petition asks that God's followers would behave in ways that are pleassing to him. 

Believers on earth are called to follow God in the same way he is obeyed in heaven

--> Petition 4: "Give us this day our daily bread"

A petition that our daily needs would be met

--> Petition 5: Forgiveness of our sins

A petition for the restoation of personal fellowship with God following sin. Asking to reconcile with God when we miss the mark

--> Petition 6: "Lead us not into temptation, deliver us from evil"

A petition to be spared circumstances that would tempt us to sin and a request to be protected from the evil enemy


That's how Jesus told us that we are to pray
- Invocation
- Praise for God's holiness
- The advancement of God's kingdom on earth
- God's will
- Ask that our needs be met
- Ask for forgiveness
- Ask for protection from evil


